    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:6a6cd296-cd5e-4b92-ae72-5bdb4e3011df",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 77-year-old retired high school history teacher who arrives neatly dressed but visibly slowed in his movements. He has a soft, slightly monotone voice, reduced facial expression, and a fine resting tremor in his right hand that becomes more obvious when he is sitting quietly. When he stands, he pauses before initiating gait, then walks with short shuffling steps, diminished arm swing, and mild stooping. His wife often answers after he hesitates, though he remains engaged and quietly humorous.\n\nAt home, {patientName} lives with his spouse in a single-story house where he used to enjoy woodworking in the garage and tending tomatoes in the backyard. Over the past two years he has cut back on both because buttoning shirts, using tools, and turning in tight spaces have become frustratingly slow. He still likes listening to baseball on the radio, doing the crossword, and taking short walks with a neighbor, but he worries about falling and has become more socially withdrawn because of embarrassment about his tremor and slowness.\n\nHis daily routine reflects a disciplined personality: breakfast early, medications lined up carefully, and a handwritten list of chores he tries to complete despite fatigue and stiffness. His sleep is fragmented, and his wife reports that he sometimes acts out dreams with kicking and talking. He struggles with constipation and occasional lightheadedness when standing. Meals take longer because of mild swallowing hesitation and reduced dexterity, though he remains independent in most basic activities.\n\nFamily and community remain central to {patientName}. He has two adult children who visit regularly and help with groceries, home repairs, and transportation to appointments. He is close to several former colleagues from the school where he taught for decades, but he now sees them less often because he feels self-conscious in crowded settings. Despite progressive symptoms, he is motivated to remain at home, preserve his independence, and continue meaningful routines with his wife and friends."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:3962b086-ce19-436a-a710-b8729f2b2a15",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a gradually progressive 3-year history of right-sided resting tremor, bradykinesia, limb rigidity, and worsening gait initiation difficulty, leading to a recent neurology diagnosis of Parkinson disease. Symptoms are worse in the morning before medication and during periods of fatigue. He reports constipation, fragmented sleep, probable REM sleep behavior symptoms, and occasional orthostatic dizziness. There is no history suggesting stroke, major head trauma, or exposure to dopamine-blocking medications.\n\nHis past medical history includes hypertension, chronic constipation, and age-related cataracts, with no prior Parkinson-related hospitalizations. He underwent cataract extraction several years ago and a screening colonoscopy in the past. He is a former smoker who quit in his 40s, drinks alcohol rarely, and has no illicit drug use. {patientName} was previously active with gardening and walking, but physical activity has declined because of stiffness, fear of falling, and slowed mobility."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
